metadata.name: Scaffold #14
metadata.description:
The thoughts we have are rarely as ordered as the words we speak and the actions we take are shaped by expectation and conditioning.

As we grow up, we are taught to behave or even think in a certain way. We learn what is acceptable and what is not. Our thoughts are forced to align with the structure imposed upon us.

Scaffold is an attempt to visually explore this concept of thoughts and control. Each output represents a state of mind at a particular moment in time.

Palettes have been mostly named by my family based on the first word they thought of when they saw them.

Keyboard commands:

s - save as png
h - toggle high resolution 
b - toggle background texture
a - switch aspect ratio
r - new moment

metadata.name: BRUTALIST MANIFESTO #61
metadata.description:
Discovered and brought into daylight from under gigantic concrete pylons of ancient digital monuments by brutologists. 

Written on multiple screens with blocks and bytes and bits in a language long forgotten.

Decyphering has already started for the sole purpose of understanding the roots of the new Brutalist Movement. 

These are the fragments of the BRUTALIST MANIFESTO.

///

Tech specs already decrypted from the fragments:

Randomized parameters
- 12 color palettes
- 5-8-10 rows
- 5-8-10 columns
- 0-8 blocks per glyphs
- 0-all special glyphs per row
- very rare occasion of a glitched glyph

Press 's' to download an image in 2k at any time of the generation.

///

Have fun decyphering!

☁︎

cloudnoise © 2022

///

Created with P5.js library.

metadata.name: Kaibō #3
metadata.description:
What would happen if we took the natural forms that surround us and dissected them into composable shapes? 

Taking the organic world of Yashinoki, Kiabō dissects organic forms into composable elements, then reforms them into precise geometric arrangements. These shapes give way to random, organic growth the closer we look at them. 


Controls in live mode:
- Press [s] to save a png

metadata.name: Part:Counterpart #30
metadata.description:
'Part:Counterpart' is an experiment in form, disintegration, and context. Each work is created within one of three modes, Part, Counterpart, or Part:Counterpart.

In experimenting, I've enjoyed taking a simple composition and breaking it down with various methods. This transforms the original composition into something new, but it also begins to lose what the original had to say. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, and I want to dive a little deeper and explore ideas as a sort of tangible substance. Already we're comparing ideas against their translations and evolutions, but what happens if we present them both within the context of the other?

Additionally, what if we present both of these ideas with echoes and tangents, discussion around the ideas and their practical applications instead of imagined? Sure, these aren't our idea, or even our translation, but they exist only because the originals do.

How does this change our opinion of the original? Is every idea destined to be picked apart and reimagined forever until it bears only a faint resemblance? Where is the line between our Counterpart and an echo?

This piece hopes to inspire contemplation on the nature of storytelling and artistic inspiration.

10% of ideas are encrypted to obscure the original Part.
Press ’s’ to save a 3600x4500 png.
Press ‘p’ to save the original Part, pure and untouched.

metadata.name: September #277
metadata.description:
The Summer Ends
---------------
Controls:
S or double tap (mobile): Download image

A: Toggle loading animation (off by default to improve performance)

1-6: Modify scale (1 = default, 1500 x 2000px, 6 = maximum, 9000 x 12000px (performance intensive, will take a long time to render))
F: Fit to current screen size

T: Toggle grain and texture overlay
H: Toggle shape outlines

B: Cycle border sizes (0 -> 50 -> 75 -> 100 -> 150px)
C: Cycle border colors

I: Cycle visible layers

L: Toggle “live mode”. This mode will continuously redraw a new output every few seconds using the same base parameters as the original output, but with slight variations.

You can modify the x and y url parameters to set a custom size. Note that the image will change to fit the new size, but overall drawing style, colors, etc. will remain the same.
(For example, for a 1000x2000 image, add &x=1000&y=2000)

metadata.name: ðolmen #138
metadata.description:
ðolmen is a generative art project by Diego Pintos.
It draws rectangles with points instead a plain color or border. With some variations in the distribution of this points, we get a kind of noise depth effect.

12 carefully selected palettes. Based in Art Masterpieces and in Nature.
· Gioconda (Leonardo da Vinci)
· Guernika (Pablo Picasso)
· Nighthawks (Edward Hopper)
· Meninas (Diego Velazquez)
· Judith beheading Holofernes (Caravaggio)
· Al Siq (nature)
· guacamayo (nature)
· Salamanca (nature)
· mostaza (nature)
· Timanfaya (nature)
· piedra (nature)
· firefall (nature)

ðolmen builds 10 compositions:
· Square
· PersonChen's Style
· Equilibrium
· Hanging
· Pyramid
· Row
· Column
· 3 columns (randomly aligned)
· 3 rows (randomly aligned)
· Frame

Density
· Tiny: Less than 35 rects. Rare
· Small: Less than 100 rects. Common.
· Medium: Less than 250 rects. Common.
· High: Less than 350 rects. Common.
· Massive: Less than 500 rects. Rare.
· Ultra: More than 500 rects. Rarest.

Rarities
· Rectangle filling type: Filled (95%) or unfilled (5%)
· Monochrome: Just black and white. Always unfilled. (1%)
· Dark mode: Dark background (20%). Dark mode can be monochrome.
· Habitable (90%). See humans later.

Humans
ðolmen can host tiny humans. Contains a little code that draws humans looking down, in order to to provide size perspective.

Minting
Each ðolmen contains all rarities inside. As a ðolmen collector, you can display your final piece in all available formats, and rarity owners can display the regular filled composition. In addition, this can help if you want to print one or more formats.

Tricks and Keys
ðolmen is responsive, you can zoom out your browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas
'd' toggle dark mode
'f' toggle fill mode
'm' toggle monochrome

More info and visual description:
https://thelirios.com/dolmen/

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0

metadata.name: SwatchLands #6
metadata.description:
SwatchLands

SwatchLands are pointillistic fields, of recycled shreds and bits of Swatch (see fx Project #11994).
Reminiscent and inspired by Rothko's large abstracts and Monet's impressionistic water lily ponds.
A continuing experiment in taming wild colors.

Native resolution is 2426x2426.

Controls:
- Press 's' to save a PNG file.
